  "prompt": "Why do bolts and nuts not get welded, when both are the same metal and their crystal structure is the same?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why bolts and nuts do not naturally weld together, even when made of the same metal:\n\n1. Oxide Layer\n- Metal surfaces are always covered with a thin oxide layer\n- This oxide layer prevents direct metal-to-metal contact\n- The oxide layer acts as a barrier to welding\n\n2. Surface Finish and Roughness\n- Bolts and nuts have precise surface finishes\n- Surface roughness prevents complete contact\n- Microscopic gaps prevent complete metallic bonding\n\n3. Mechanical Contact Conditions\n- Bolts and nuts are designed with specific tolerances\n- They are not under conditions that promote atomic diffusion\n- Welding requires high temperature, pressure, and prolonged contact\n\n4. Lubrication and Coatings\n- Often, bolts and nuts are coated with anti-seize compounds\n- These coatings prevent direct metal contact\n- Lubricants create a barrier to welding\n\n5. Low Compressive Pressure\n- Welding requires high compressive pressure\n- Bolt and nut connections have limited contact pressure\n- Insufficient pressure prevents atomic diffusion\n\n6. Lack of High Temperature\n- Welding requires temperatures near metal's melting point\n- Typical bolt connections do not generate such temperatures\n\nThese factors collectively prevent spontaneous welding between bolts and nuts.",
